<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-527-863  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 527 863  OV: 09 527 831.andM; </DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Oct 22 1990 v7 n42 p116(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>cc:Mail Inc.: cc;Mail LAN Package 3.15; cc:Mail LAN Package forMacintosh 1.15. (Software Review) (one of four evaluations ofelectronic mail packages in 'Software delivers the mail to Macs,PCs.') (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Van Name, Mark L.; Catchings, Bill.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>The combination of cc:Mail Inc's cc:Mail LAN Package 3.15 andcc:Mail LAN Package for Macintosh 1.15 lets users send and receiveelectronic mail between networked Macintoshes and IBM-compatiblePCs while providing better overall mail features than competingproducts.andP;  The system is geared toward PCs, but the Mac version issolid enough to be useful.andP;  cc:Mail stores all messages in acentral database instead of using a mail-server program.andP;  Thedatabase keeps only one copy of each message with multiplerecipients and encrypts all messages for security.andP;  Onedisadvantage is the fact that users must always set up the networkvolume containing the E-mail database.andP;  cc:Mail currently requiresa PC for its administrative functions; a Mac administrator will beavailable in Nov 1990.andP;  The Mac cc:Mail client package does notimplement the Mac interface well; its main program cannot run as adesk accessory, and the Notify program is a desk accessory insteadof an automatic INIT.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   CC:Mail Inc. (products).andO;Product:   cc:Mail LAN Package 3.15 (Electronic mail system)cc:Mail LAN Package for Macintosh 1.15 (Electronic mail system).andO;Topic:     Electronic Mail SystemsEvaluationSoftware PackagesConnectivity.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Vital signs. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>cc:Mail Inc.andM;CC:MAIL LAN PACKAGE 3.15, CC:MAIL LAN PACKAGE FOR MACINTOSH 1.15andM;cc:Mail provides the best overall mail facilities of the group.andP;  While gearedtoward PCs, its Mac version is good enough to make it a good choice for mostgroups.andM;cc:Mail does not use a mail-server program.andP;  Instead, it stores all messagesin a central database.andP;  Any system that can access that database can exchangemessages.andP;  cc:Mail manages that database well, keeping only one copy of eachmessage with multiple recipients.andP;  It also encrypts all messages for addedsecurity.andM;By using a central database, cc:Mail can work on any network that lets PCsand Macs share files.andP;  The lack of a mail-server program, however, has onebad side effect: Users must always set up the network volume that containsthe E-mail database.andM;cc:Mail reveals its PC heritage in several ways, most notably by requiring aPC for its administrative functions.andP;  A Mac administrator option, however, isdue for shipment in late November.andP;  The product's PC user interface isnon-standard but easy to use.andP;  It includes an 86K-byte TSR program forreading messages.andM;Administrative functions aside, cc:Mail's Mac version offers the samefeatures as its PC-based counterpart.andP;  The Mac product, however, is not veryMac-like.andP;  The main program cannot run as a desk accessory (DA), which makesit a hassle to use from within other programs.andP;  The Notify program, whichshould be an INIT program that runs automatically, is instead a DA.andP;  Inaddition, Mac users must perform a clumsy procedure for specifying thelocation of the mail database every time they start cc:Mail.andM;The documentation is generally strong, although the Mac manuals are a bitsparse.andM;cc:Mail Inc.andM;Mountain View, Calif.andP;  (415) 961-8800andM;Privately heldandM;Year established: 1983andM;Number of employees: 55 (1)andM;Gross annual revenue (1990): $7.5 million (1)andM;Gross annual earnings (1990): not disclosed (1)andM;Source: On-Line DataSources.andM;(1) Information supplied by the company.andM;</TEXT></DOC>